<br>
Before EQ I played a game I was addicted to.  It was called Dragonrealms (<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.dragonrealms.net">www.dragonrealms.net</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.  It was basd on percentages being in constant movement upwards to get one point in a skill.  Have a certain requirements in a skill and you would get levels.<br>
<br>
To work percentages you would use the skills, if you had heavy weapons, you would fight a creature and the percentages would start to increase.  Need to learn first aid, you would tend a bleeding wound.<br>
<br>
Now some of the skills were so horrible to learn, that to just level, a cehat was developed to help this along (which is what we all wish we could do for trade skills) which was called scripting.  You would write a script in a basic like code to have them done by you in the game.  So you would type something and and just let it go.  Well if you were caught, you got warnings, kep it up you got banned.  SOme of us were a bit more sneaky and got away with it by other means.  My main was a Pallie and so I could not script him too much, but my rogue and my moonmage (teleporter and assassin) did it all the time.  I scripted pick pocketing so much I could steal items from vendors but could not open a chest.<br>
<br>
Did I mention this game is text based.  Yeah, it was, but it was still fun.<br>
<br>
The problem is when it moved off of AOL (the only reason I kept AOL) it became money hungry.  There were things called Fests (Festivals) in which a temporary game area was opened full of rare hard to find items that people would spend 4 months hunting and saving up money for.  They started out as free, then later on people had to pay 10 - 20$ to go to them.<br>
<br>
Then DR opened up the premium accounts.  For 20$ a month you could get nifty in game items, and access to hunting spots that would not be accessable to non-premium accounts.  My favorite spot for that was Gargols outside one of the starting cities.  I spent months hunting there and making serious gold and plat (plat was inordinately hard to get, one plat in that game was equal to a K in ours).  Then the next thing I know what once was an almost empty area, now had a player in each room, and not enough gargs spawned to handle that.<br>
<br>
Finally they opened their own legends type server and it was all over.  I had friends tell me about Everquest, and that it was graphical, and so I bought the software and signed up, made a monk on Bertoxulous and found a new world that wowwed me.]<br>
<br>
I don't think I have gotten to the point in EQ that I did in DR.  There are still some cool things I want to do before being driven to that point. <br>
<br>
